Given the time, I will produce a fix that makes the factory delegate to gson to get a proper adapter for the exact type, if available. This is a common pattern: in Gson, hierarchy factories often call gson.getDelegateAdapter(this, typeToken) for subtypes. So the fix would be:

return new TypeAdapterFactory() {
  public <T2> TypeAdapter<T2> create(Gson gson, TypeToken<T2> typeToken) {
    final Class<? super T2> requestedType = typeToken.getRawType();
    if (!clazz.isAssignableFrom(requestedType)) {
      return null;
    }
    // If the requested type is exactly the same, use the provided adapter
    if (clazz.equals(requestedType)) {
      return (TypeAdapter<T2>) typeAdapter;
    }
    // Otherwise, delegate to get the adapter for the subtype, which might be the same or a different one
    return gson.getDelegateAdapter(this, typeToken);
  }
};

This ensures that for subclasses, the factory delegates to other registered adapters, including potentially a more specific adapter for the subclass. This would fix the issue where an adapter for the superclass is incorrectly used for subclasses that have their own adapters. This is a minimal fix that preserves the hierarchy behavior for exact type and delegates for subclasses.

